  "description": "<h2 id=\"introduction\">Introduction</h2>\n<p>Near the town of Tzimol, the San Vicente River turbulent waters\ncreate a majestic set of waterfalls as they descend down the mountain.\nThese waterfalls are named 'El Suspiro', 'Ala de Ángel', 'Arcoíris',\n'Quinceañera' y 'Velo de Novia' (the tallest at 70m), and are\ncollectively known as 'Cascadas El Chiflón' and abbreviated as\n'Chiflón'. Two commercial Ecotouristic centers, one located at each side\nof the river, cater to tourists providing hiking trails to access\nviewing platforms and swimming holes created by the falls.</p>\n<p>This area is also home of a kick-ass canyoneering route called 'Three\nTzemoleras'. Local adventure companies (Xaman, Petra and Explora) joined\nforces and run the first descent of this canyon in 2015 and will be\noffering this trip publicly in 2016.</p>\n<p>Experienced canyoneers may also choose to descend this canyoneering\nroute on their own, as long as they use proper techniques and don't get\ninto trouble.</p>\n<h2 id=\"approach\">Approach</h2>\n<p>The route requires a shuttle. Leave a vehicle at the exit of Chiflon\nand with another vehicles transfer up the mountain to the town of\nTzemoleras.</p>\n<p>The road to Tzemoleras is said to require a 4 wheel drive vehicle. If\nyou don't have any, arrange transport with some of the locals. Given the\ndistance from Tuxla, it may be preferable to arrange to stay for the\nnight at Tzemoleras to start the canyon fresh the next morning.</p>\n<p>The location of the approach and drop in point in the map are\napproximations, please contact James Wright (Xaman) for more\ninformation.</p>\n<h2 id=\"descent\">Descent</h2>\n<p>The descent includes 3 main waterfalls of 30m, 60m &amp; 70m high\nplus several smaller ones all the way to Chiflon (the area of the river\ncontrolled by the cooperativas)</p>\n<h2 id=\"exit\">Exit</h2>\n<p>Hike down the tourists trails to the parking lot and your\nvehicle.</p>\n<h2 id=\"red_tape\">Red tape</h2>\n<ul>\n<li>as of late September 2021, we were told (by the ejido on the UCR\nside of the river) that it is not permitted to run this canyon. It was\nunclear whether this was due to the high flow at the time or whether\nthis would apply year-round. Follow ups in the dry season would help to\nclarify the situation. We could find no information about the guide\ncompanies Xaman or Petra in either Comitan or near the tourist\nsite.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The 'cooperativas' that run 'Chiflon' refuse permission to rappel the\nfalls to commercial companies, claiming they want to run their own\ncanyoneering trips in future. It is not clear if they would be more\npermissive with private groups.</p>\n<h2 id=\"beta_sites\">Beta sites</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a\nhref=\"http://www.turismochiapas.gob.mx/sectur/cascadas-el-chifln\">http://www.turismochiapas.gob.mx/sectur/cascadas-el-chifln</a></li>\n<li><a\nhref=\"http://www.mexicodesconocido.com.mx/guia-de-cascadas-de-chiapas.html\">http://www.mexicodesconocido.com.mx/guia-de-cascadas-de-chiapas.html</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"trip_reports_and_media\">Trip reports and media</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a\nhref=\"https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.1706052862947235.1073741859.1482144422004748&amp;type=3\">https://www.facebook.com/media/set/?set=a.1706052862947235.1073741859.1482144422004748&amp;type=3</a>\nFacebook Album first descent</li>\n</ul>\n<h2 id=\"background\">Background</h2>\n<p>Original information provided by James Wright (Xaman) and Carlos\nMacotela (Petra).</p>\n",
